<section xml:id="sec-decimal_expansions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>
    Decimal Expansions
  </title>

<introduction>

    <p>
        We have defined the natural numbers, integers, rational numbers, and irrational numbers, but up to this point we have made no effort to define the real numbers. 
        There are many approaches to define the real numbers, but we will take a somewhat simplistic (but still useful!) view involving decimal expansions. 
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-real_number">
        <notation>
            <usage> <m> \R </m> </usage>
          <description> real numbers </description>
        </notation>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A <term> real number </term> is a number which has a decimal expansion. The set of all real numbers is denoted <m> \R </m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        There are two types of decimal expansions for real numbers, which can be informally described as follows:
    </p>

    <ul>
        <li>
            Finite/terminating decimals such as <m> 6.125 </m>, <m> 5.1 </m>, and <m> 0.0000123456789 </m>.
        </li>
        <li>
            Infinite/non-terminating decimals such as <m> 4.333\ldots = 4.\overline{3} </m> and <m> 0.127666\ldots=0.127\overline{6} </m>.
        </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        In order to formally define and analyze these types of decimal expansions, we will utilize the following notation:
    </p>
    <me>
        D.d_1d_2d_3d_4\cdots
    </me>
    <p>
        where <m> D </m> is a non-negative integer and <m> d_1,d_2,d_3,d_4,\ldots </m> are digits (<m> 0,1,\ldots,9 </m>). 
        For example, the number <m> 6.125 </m> is represented with <m> D=6 </m>, <m> d_1=1 </m>, <m> d_2=2 </m>, <m> d_3=5 </m>, 
        and <m> d_n=0 </m> for all <m> n \geq 4 </m>; the number <m> 0.166666\ldots=0.1\overline{6} </m> is represented by <m> D=0 </m>, <m> d_1=1 </m>, 
        and <m> d_n=6 </m> for <m> n\geq 2 </m>.
    </p>

</introduction>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-finite_infinite_decimals"  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>
        Finate and Infinite Decimals
    </title>
    
    <p>
        The notions of finite and infinite decimals are easily understood, but for purposes of discussion we need to have definitions for each.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-finite_decimal">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A <term> finite decimal </term> <m> x=D.d_1d_2\cdots d_t </m> is defined as the number
                    <me>
                        x = D + \dfrac{d_1}{10} + \dfrac{d_2}{10^2} + \cdots + \dfrac{d_t}{10^t}
                    </me>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        Note that finite decimals are finite sums of rational numbers, and therefore all finite decimals must be rational by <xref ref="thm-properties_of_rationals" />(a).
    </p>

    <example>
        <p>
            We can use <xref ref="def-finite_decimal" /> to write the number <m> 6.125 </m> as a fraction.
        </p>
        <md>
            <mrow> 6.125 \amp= 6 + \dfrac{1}{10} + \dfrac{2}{10^2} + \dfrac{5}{10^3} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= 6 + \dfrac{1}{10} + \dfrac{2}{100} + \dfrac{5}{1000} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= 6 + \dfrac{100}{1000} + \dfrac{20}{1000} + \dfrac{5}{1000} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= 6 + \dfrac{125}{1000} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= 6 + \dfrac{1}{8} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= \dfrac{49}{8} </mrow>
        </md>
    </example>

    <definition xml:id="def-infinite_decimal" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
        <statement>
            <p>
                An <term> infinite decimal </term> <m> x = D.d_1d_2d_3\ldots d_n\ldots </m> is defined as either
            </p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    the limit of the sequence of finite decimals <m> D </m>, <m> D.d_1 </m>, <m> D.d_1d_2 </m>, <m> D.d_1d_2d_3 </m>, <m> \ldots </m>
                </li>
                <li>
                    the sum of the series <m> D + \displaystyle\sum_{i=0}^{\infty} \dfrac{d_i}{10^i} </m>.
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <remark>
        <p>
            The equivalence of the two definitions of infinite decimals should be clear from the definition of series convergence in calculus.
            Recall that a geometric series is a series of the form
        </p>
        <me> 
            \displaystyle\sum_{i=0}^{\infty} a\cdot r^{n-1} = a + ar + ar^2 + ar^3 + \cdots
        </me>.
        <p>
            A geometric series converges when <m> |r| \lt 1 </m>, and in this case the sum of the series is <m> \dfrac{a}{1-r} </m>.
        </p>
    </remark>


</subsection>



</section>